Creating a basic stopwatch application using XAML involves designing the user interface and implementing the logic to start, stop, and reset the stopwatch. Below is a simple example of how you might create a stopwatch in a WPF (Windows Presentation Foundation) application using XAML and C#.

### XAML Code

This is the XAML code for your stopwatch application. It includes a label to display the time and three buttons to control the stopwatch: Start, Stop, and Reset.

```xml
<Window x:Class="StopwatchApp.MainWindow"
        xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        Title="Stopwatch" Height="150" Width="300">
    <Grid>
        <Label Name="TimeLabel" Content="00:00:00" HorizontalAlignment="Center" VerticalAlignment="Top" FontSize="24" Margin="0,20"/>
        <Button Name="StartButton" Content="Start" HorizontalAlignment="Left" VerticalAlignment="Bottom" Width="75" Click="StartButton_Click"/>
        <Button Name="StopButton" Content="Stop" HorizontalAlignment="Center" VerticalAlignment="Bottom" Width="75" Click="StopButton_Click"/>
        <Button Name="ResetButton" Content="Reset" HorizontalAlignment="Right" VerticalAlignment="Bottom" Width="75" Click="ResetButton_Click"/>
    </Grid>
</Window>
```

### C# Code-Behind

This is the C# code that will handle the logic for starting, stopping, and resetting the stopwatch. This code should be placed in the `MainWindow.xaml.cs` file.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Diagnostics;
using System.Windows;

namespace StopwatchApp
{
    public partial class MainWindow : Window
    {
        private Stopwatch stopwatch = new Stopwatch();
        private DispatcherTimer timer = new DispatcherTimer();

        public MainWindow()
        {
            InitializeComponent();
            timer.Interval = TimeSpan.FromMilliseconds(100); // Update every 100ms
            timer.Tick += Timer_Tick;
        }

        private void StartButton_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
        {
            if (!stopwatch.IsRunning)
            {
                stopwatch.Start();
                timer.Start();
            }
        }

        private void StopButton_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
        {
            if (stopwatch.IsRunning)
            {
                stopwatch.Stop();
            }
        }

        private void ResetButton_Click(object sender, RoutedEventArgs e)
        {
            stopwatch.Reset();
            TimeLabel.Content = "00:00:00";
        }

        private void Timer_Tick(object sender, EventArgs e)
        {
            TimeSpan ts = stopwatch.Elapsed;
            string elapsedTime = String.Format("{0:00}:{1:00}:{2:00}.{3:00}",
                ts.Minutes, ts.Seconds, ts.Milliseconds / 10, ts.Milliseconds % 10);
            TimeLabel.Content = elapsedTime;
        }
    }
}
```

### Explanation

- **XAML**: Defines the layout of the UI with a label to show the elapsed time and three buttons to control the stopwatch.
- **C#**:
  - Initializes a `Stopwatch` object to measure elapsed time.
  - Uses a `DispatcherTimer` to update the UI every 100 milliseconds.
  - Handles button clicks to start, stop, and reset the stopwatch.
  - Updates the time displayed on the label according to the elapsed time measured by the stopwatch.

To run this application, you need to have a WPF project setup in Visual Studio or any other compatible IDE. Make sure to replace `StopwatchApp` with your actual namespace.

