Here is an example of a React component that uses `react-query` to fetch data from an API. For this example, let's assume we're fetching user data from a hypothetical API endpoint.

First, ensure you have a React project set up. If you don't, you can create one using Create React App:

```bash
npx create-react-app my-app
cd my-app
npm start
```

Then, create a new component named `UserList.js`. This component will use `react-query` to fetch and display a list of users.

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query';

// Function to fetch data from the API
const fetchUsers = async () => {
  const response = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users');
  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error('Network response was not ok');
  }
  return response.json();
};

const UserList = () => {
  // Use the useQuery hook to fetch the data
  const { isLoading, error, data } = useQuery(['users'], fetchUsers);

  if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>;
  if (error) return <p>Error fetching data</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>User List</h1>
      <ul>
        {data.map(user => (
          <li key={user.id}>
            {user.name} - {user.email}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export default UserList;
```

In this example:
- The `fetchUsers` function makes an HTTP GET request to the specified URL and returns the JSON data.
- The `useQuery` hook from `react-query` is used to manage the fetching state. It takes two arguments: a query key (an array that uniquely identifies this query) and a function that fetches the data.
- The component renders different UI states based on whether the data is loading, there's an error, or the data has been successfully fetched.

Remember to import and use the `UserList` component in your main application file (e.g., `App.js`):

```jsx
import React from 'react';
import UserList from './UserList';

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <UserList />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

