To connect your Android application to a WebSocket server configured with Spring Boot, SockJS, and STOMP, you will need to use a library that supports these protocols. One of the most popular libraries for this purpose is `OkHttp` combined with `Stomp-over-WebSocket`.

Here's a step-by-step guide to help you set up your Android application to communicate with your WebSocket server:

### Step 1: Add Dependencies

First, add the necessary dependencies to your `build.gradle` file.

```gradle
dependencies {
    implementation 'com.squareup.okhttp3:okhttp:4.9.0'
    implementation 'org.java-websocket:Java-WebSocket:1.5.2'
}
```

Note: The version numbers might be different depending on the latest available versions at the time of your setup.

### Step 2: Initialize WebSocket Connection

Create a class to manage the WebSocket connection and communication with your server. Below is an example of how you can initialize the WebSocket connection using OkHttp and Java-WebSocket.

```java
import okhttp3.OkHttpClient;
import okhttp3.Request;
import okhttp3.WebSocket;

public class WebSocketClient {

    private OkHttpClient client;
    private WebSocket webSocket;

    public WebSocketClient(String url) {
        client = new OkHttpClient();
        Request request = new Request.Builder().url(url).build();
        webSocket = client.newWebSocket(request, new WebSocketListener());
    }

    // Implement WebSocketListener to handle messages, errors, etc.
    private class WebSocketListener extends WebSocketListener {
        @Override
        public void onOpen(WebSocket webSocket, Response response) {
            super.onOpen(webSocket, response);
            // Connected successfully
        }

        @Override
        public void onMessage(WebSocket webSocket, String text) {
            super.onMessage(webSocket, text);
            // Handle incoming messages here
        }

        @Override
        public void onFailure(WebSocket webSocket, Throwable t, Response response) {
            super.onFailure(webSocket, t, response);
            // Handle failure
        }
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Connect Using SockJS and STOMP

For SockJS and STOMP, you may want to use a more specialized library like `spring-android-stomp`. However, this library is not actively maintained. An alternative approach would be to manually implement the SockJS protocol over WebSocket and handle STOMP messages yourself or find another suitable library.

If you decide to use a custom approach, you'll need to:

1. **Connect to the SockJS endpoint** (usually `/ws` or `/stomp`).
2. **Handle the SockJS protocol** (which involves reconnecting if needed and handling different transport types).
3. **Send and receive STOMP frames**.

Below is a simplified example of connecting to a SockJS endpoint and sending a STOMP message:

```java
import okhttp3.OkHttpClient;
import okhttp3.Request;
import okhttp3.WebSocket;

public class SockJsWebSocketClient {

    private OkHttpClient client;
    private WebSocket webSocket;

    public SockJsWebSocketClient(String url) {
        client = new OkHttpClient();
        Request request = new Request.Builder().url(url).build();
        webSocket = client.newWebSocket(request, new WebSocketListener());
    }

    private class WebSocketListener extends WebSocketListener {
        @Override
        public void onOpen(WebSocket webSocket, Response response) {
            super.onOpen(webSocket, response);
            // Send a STOMP CONNECT frame
            String stompConnectFrame = "CONNECT\naccept-version:1.1,1.2\nheart-beat:10000,10000\n\n\0";
            webSocket.send(stompConnectFrame);
        }

        @Override
        public void onMessage(WebSocket webSocket, String text) {
            super.onMessage(webSocket, text);
            // Handle incoming messages here
        }

        @Override
        public void onFailure(WebSocket webSocket, Throwable t, Response response) {
            super.onFailure(webSocket, t, response);
            // Handle failure
        }
    }
}
```

This is a very basic example. In practice, you would need to handle various aspects of the SockJS protocol and STOMP messaging in detail.

### Conclusion

Connecting your Android app to a Spring Boot backend using WebSocket, SockJS, and STOMP requires careful handling of both the WebSocket connection and the messaging protocol. Depending on your specific needs, you may choose to use a specialized library or implement parts of the protocol manually.

