To add a button in a React Native iOS app that opens up the camera, you can use the `react-native-camera` library or the more modern and flexible `expo-camera` if you're using Expo. Below is an example using `expo-camera`. If you're not using Expo, I'll also provide instructions for `react-native-camera`.

### Using Expo Camera

First, ensure you have Expo installed and set up. Then, install the `expo-camera` package:

```bash
expo install expo-camera
```

Here's how you can create a simple component with a button that opens the camera:

```jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { Button, View, StyleSheet } from 'react-native';
import * as Camera from 'expo-camera';

export default function App() {
  const [hasPermission, setHasPermission] = useState(null);
  const [cameraRef, setCameraRef] = useState(null);

  React.useEffect(() => {
    (async () => {
      const { status } = await Camera.requestPermissionsAsync();
      setHasPermission(status === 'granted');
    })();
  }, []);

  const openCamera = async () => {
    if (hasPermission) {
      await cameraRef.showCameraPreview();
    } else if (hasPermission === null) {
      alert('Requesting for camera permission');
    } else {
      alert('Permission to access camera was denied');
    }
  };

  return (
    <View style={styles.container}>
      <Button title="Open Camera" onPress={openCamera} />
      {hasPermission && <Camera.Camera ref={(ref) => setCameraRef(ref)} style={styles.camera} />}
    </View>
  );
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  container: {
    flex: 1,
    justifyContent: 'center',
    alignItems: 'center',
  },
  camera: {
    width: '100%',
    height: '80%',
  },
});
```

### Using react-native-camera

If you're not using Expo, you would typically use `react-native-camera`. First, install the necessary packages:

```bash
npm install react-native-camera
# or
yarn add react-native-camera
```

And then link the native modules (if required):

```bash
react-native link react-native-camera
```

Here's how you can implement it:

```jsx
import React, { useRef } from 'react';
import { Button, View, StyleSheet } from 'react-native';
import { RNCamera } from 'react-native-camera';

export default function App() {
  const cameraRef = useRef(null);

  const openCamera = () => {
    if (cameraRef.current) {
      cameraRef.current.resumePreview();
    }
  };

  return (
    <View style={styles.container}>
      <Button title="Open Camera" onPress={openCamera} />
      <RNCamera
        ref={cameraRef}
        style={styles.preview}
        type={RNCamera.Constants.Type.back}
        flashMode={RNCamera.Constants.FlashMode.on}
        androidCameraPermissionOptions={{
          title: 'Permission to use camera',
          message: 'We need your permission to use your camera',
          buttonPositive: 'Ok',
          buttonNegative: 'Cancel',
        }}
      >
        {/* View inside RNCamera will be ignored */}
      </RNCamera>
    </View>
  );
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
  container: {
    flex: 1,
    flexDirection: 'column',
    backgroundColor: 'black',
  },
  preview: {
    flex: 1,
    justifyContent: 'flex-end',
    alignItems: 'center',
  },
});
```

In both examples, make sure to handle permissions properly according to your app's needs and platform requirements.

