Certainly! Below is an example of how you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to dynamically adjust the width of an `iframe` based on the viewport width.

### HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Responsive Iframe</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <iframe id="responsiveIframe" src="https://www.example.com" frameborder="0"></iframe>
    </div>
    <script src="scripts.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (styles.css):
```css
body, html {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    height: 100%;
}

.container {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    height: 100%;
}
```

### JavaScript (scripts.js):
```javascript
function setIframeWidth() {
    const iframe = document.getElementById('responsiveIframe');
    const viewportWidth = window.innerWidth;

    if (viewportWidth <= 360) {
        iframe.style.width = '360px';
    } else if (viewportWidth <= 720) {
        iframe.style.width = '720px';
    } else {
        iframe.style.width = '1400px';
    }
}

// Set the iframe width initially
setIframeWidth();

// Listen for changes in window size and update the iframe width accordingly
window.addEventListener('resize', setIframeWidth);
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML**: The HTML file includes a container `div` with an `iframe`. The `iframe` has an ID of `responsiveIframe`, which we'll use to manipulate its properties with JavaScript.

2. **CSS**: This simple CSS ensures that the body and HTML elements take up the full height of the viewport and centers the `iframe` inside the container.

3. **JavaScript**:
   - The `setIframeWidth` function checks the current width of the viewport using `window.innerWidth`.
   - Based on the width, it sets the `width` style property of the `iframe`.
   - The function is called once when the page loads to set the initial width.
   - An event listener is added to the window's `resize` event to call `setIframeWidth` whenever the window size changes, ensuring the `iframe` resizes dynamically.

This setup will ensure your `iframe` adjusts its width according to the defined breakpoints (360px, 720px, and 1400px).

