To integrate WordPress comments posting functionality into a Next.js application with authentication, you will need to use the WordPress REST API for handling the comment submission and some form of authentication to secure the process. Below is a simplified guide on how you can achieve this:

### Step 1: Set Up Authentication

Firstly, you need to set up an authentication mechanism for your Next.js app to communicate securely with the WordPress REST API. One common way is to use OAuth or JSON Web Tokens (JWT). For simplicity, we'll use JWT here.

#### 1.1 Install Required Packages

In your Next.js project, install `jsonwebtoken` and `axios`:

```bash
npm install jsonwebtoken axios
```

#### 1.2 Generate JWT Token

You can generate a JWT token server-side when a user logs in or directly from your WordPress site if it supports JWT authentication.

### Step 2: Create a Comment Submission Function

Create a function that sends a POST request to the WordPress REST API to submit a comment.

#### 2.1 Create an API Route in Next.js

Create a file named `[comment].js` inside the `pages/api` directory:

```javascript
// pages/api/comment.js
import axios from 'axios';

export default async function handler(req, res) {
    if (req.method === 'POST') {
        const { postId, authorName, authorEmail, content, token } = req.body;

        try {
            // Make sure to replace 'your-wordpress-site' with your actual WordPress site URL
            const response = await axios.post(
                'https://your-wordpress-site/wp-json/wp/v2/comments',
                {
