To achieve the effect where the navigation bar hides on scroll down and shows on scroll up with a sliding animation, while disabling this behavior on pages that don't require scrolling (plus some slack), you can use JavaScript along with CSS. Below is an example implementation:

### HTML Structure
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Scrolling Navigation</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <nav id="navbar">
        <ul>
            <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
            <li><a href="#services">Services</a></li>
            <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
        </ul>
    </nav>
    <div id="content">
        <!-- Your content here -->
    </div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (styles.css)
```css
body {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

#navbar {
    position: fixed;
    top: 0;
    width: 100%;
    background-color: #333;
    color: white;
    z-index: 1000;
    transition: top 0.3s ease-in-out;
}

#navbar ul {
    list-style-type: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
}

#navbar ul li {
    margin: 0 15px;
}

#navbar ul li a {
    text-decoration: none;
    color: white;
    padding: 15px 20px;
    display: block;
}

.hidden {
    top: -60px; /* Adjust based on your nav height */
}
```

### JavaScript (script.js)
```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    const navbar = document.getElementById('navbar');
    let lastScrollPosition = window.pageYOffset || document.documentElement.scrollTop;

    // Check if the page needs to scroll
    const hasScroll = document.body.scrollHeight > window.innerHeight + 100; // Add some slack

    function handleScroll() {
        const currentScrollPosition = window.pageYOffset || document.documentElement.scrollTop;

        if (!hasScroll) {
            navbar.classList.remove('hidden');
            return;
        }

        if (currentScrollPosition > lastScrollPosition && !navbar.classList.contains('hidden')) {
            navbar.classList.add('hidden');
        } else if (currentScrollPosition < lastScrollPosition && navbar.classList.contains('hidden')) {
            navbar.classList.remove('hidden');
        }

        lastScrollPosition = currentScrollPosition <= 0 ? 0 : currentScrollPosition;
    }

    window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
});
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML**: Basic structure with a `nav` element for the navigation bar and a `div` for the content.
2. **CSS**:
   - The `#navbar` is styled to be fixed at the top of the page.
   - A `.hidden` class is defined to move the navbar off-screen when hidden.
3. **JavaScript**:
   - Checks if the page has enough content to scroll by comparing the document's scroll height to the viewport height plus some slack.
   - Listens for the scroll event and toggles the `hidden` class on the navbar based on the scroll direction.

This setup ensures that the navigation bar will slide in and out as you scroll, but it won't animate on pages that don't have enough content to scroll.

