To provide an analysis of the Big O efficiency of a `hasMatchingData` method, I would need to see the implementation details of that specific method. Since you haven't provided the code for the `hasMatchingData` method, I can give you a general idea based on common scenarios.

Assuming `hasMatchingData` is a method that checks if there's matching data between two collections (like arrays or lists), the Big O notation can vary depending on how the method is implemented. Here are a few possibilities:

1. **Linear Search**: If the method simply iterates through one collection and checks each element against all elements in another collection, it might look something like this:
   ```java
   public boolean hasMatchingData(List<Integer> list1, List<Integer> list2) {
       for (Integer item : list1) {
           if (list2.contains(item)) {
               return true;
           }
       }
       return false;
   }
   ```
   In this case, the `contains` operation within the loop could potentially iterate over the entire second list for every element in the first list, leading to a time complexity of O(n * m), where n is the length of `list1` and m is the length of `list2`.

2. **Using Sets for Faster Lookups**: If the method uses sets to store elements from one collection and then checks the presence of elements from the other collection in this set, the time complexity can be significantly reduced:
   ```java
   public boolean hasMatchingData(List<Integer> list1, List<Integer> list2) {
       Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>(list1);
       for (Integer item : list2) {
           if (set.contains(item)) {
               return true;
           }
       }
       return false;
   }
   ```
   In this case, the time complexity would be O(n + m), where n is the number of elements in `list1` (for creating the set) and m is the number of elements in `list2` (for checking their presence in the set).

3. **Sorting and Binary Search**: If the method sorts both collections and then uses binary search to find matches, the complexity would involve sorting (O(n log n + m log m)) and searching (O(min(n, m) log max(n, m))), resulting in a total complexity of O((n + m) log(max(n, m))).

Without the actual code, it's hard to determine the exact Big O efficiency. If you provide the specific implementation of the `hasMatchingData` method, I can give you a more precise analysis.

Implementing an iframe server-side in Next.js 13 involves creating a dynamic or static page that will be rendered on the server and then embedded into another page using an iframe. Below is a step-by-step guide to achieve this:

### Step 1: Set Up Your Next.js Project

If you haven't already set up your Next.js project, you can do so with the following commands:

```bash
npx create-next-app@latest my-iframe-project
cd my-iframe-project
```

### Step 2: Create a Page for the Iframe Content

Create a new file inside the `pages` directory (or `app` directory if you're using the new app router) that will serve as the content of the iframe. For example, let's name it `iframe-content`.

#### Using Pages Router

If you're using the pages router, create a file named `iframe-content.js` or `iframe-content.jsx` under the `pages` directory.

```jsx
// pages/iframe-content.js
export default function IframeContent() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>This is the content that will be shown in the iframe</h1>
            <p>You can add any content here.</p>
        </div>
    );
}
```

#### Using App Router

If you're using the new app router, create a file named `page.js` or `page.jsx` under the `app/iframe-content` directory.

```jsx
// app/iframe-content/page.js
export default function IframeContent() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>This is the content that will be shown in the iframe</h1>
            <p>You can add any content here.</p>
        </div>
    );
}
```

### Step 3: Embed the Iframe in Another Page

Now, you can embed this content into another page using an `<iframe>` tag.

#### Using Pages Router

Edit `index.js` or `index.jsx` under the `pages` directory to include the iframe.

```jsx
// pages/index.js
export default function Home() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Welcome to the main page</h1>
            <iframe title="Iframe Example" src="/iframe-content" width="600" height="400"></iframe>
        </div>
    );
}
```

#### Using App Router

Edit `page.js` or `page.jsx` under the `app` directory to include the iframe.

```jsx
// app/page.js
export default function Home() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Welcome to the main page</h1>
            <iframe title="Iframe Example" src="/iframe-content" width="600" height="400"></iframe>
        </div>
    );
}
```

### Step 4: Run Your Application

Start your Next.js application with the following command:

```bash
npm run dev
```

Visit `http://localhost:3000` in your browser, and you should see the main page with the iframe embedded, displaying the content from the `/iframe-content` route.

### Notes:
- The `src` attribute of the `<iframe>` tag is set to the URL path of the page you want to display inside the iframe.
- The `title` attribute is used for accessibility purposes and should describe the purpose of the iframe.
- Adjust the `width` and `height` attributes according to your needs.

This setup demonstrates how to create and embed an iframe in a Next.js 13 application. The content of the iframe is server-rendered and can be dynamically generated based on your requirements.
